<figure id="attachment_2329" style="max-width: 150px" class="wp-caption alignright"><a href="http://www.shms.edu/content/dr-eduardo-j-echeverria"><img class="wp-image-2329 size-thumbnail" src="/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/EduardoEcheverria-150x150.jpg" alt="Prof. Eduardo J. Echeverria" width="150" height="150" srcset="/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/EduardoEcheverria-150x150.jpg 150w, /wp-content/uploads/2015/11/EduardoEcheverria-300x300.jpg 300w, /wp-content/uploads/2015/11/EduardoEcheverria-768x768.jpg 768w, /wp-content/uploads/2015/11/EduardoEcheverria-100x100.jpg 100w, /wp-content/uploads/2015/11/EduardoEcheverria.jpg 1000w" sizes="(max-width: 150px) 100vw, 150px" /></a><figcaption class="wp-caption-text">Prof. Eduardo J. Echeverria</figcaption></figure>
<p>Echeverria addresses whether neo-Calvinists such as Kuyper, Bavinck, and Dooyeweerd were correct in their criticism of an alleged two-story (i.e., dualistic) “textbook” view of the <em>duplex ordo cognoscendi</em> or the relation between nature and grace in Roman Catholic thought.</p>
<p>Listeners interested in this wide-ranging topic should note that Echeverria further develops his criticism of neo-Calvinism’s view of the <em>duplex ordo</em> in Roman Catholic thought in <em><a href="http://www.brill.com/berkouwer-and-catholicism">Berkouwer and Catholicism</a></em> (Brill, 2013).</p>
